<methodology slug="backlog-grooming-roadmapping">
  <metadata>
    <tier>solo</tier>
    <group>sdd</group>
    <domain>sdd</domain>
    <summary>Weekly backlog grooming with RICE/MoSCoW scoring. Roadmapping via Now/Next/Later horizons, not dates.</summary>
    <category>sdd</category>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-26</created>
    <tags>
      <tag>backlog</tag>
      <tag>grooming</tag>
      <tag>roadmap</tag>
      <tag>prioritization</tag>
      <tag>rice</tag>
      <tag>moscow</tag>
    </tags>
    <tools>
      <tool>claude-code</tool>
    </tools>
    <applies-to>both</applies-to>
  </metadata>

  <content>
    <title>Backlog Grooming and Roadmapping</title>

    <summary>Backlog grooming is the weekly practice of scoring, reordering, and refining items in `.aidocs/backlog/` using RICE or MoSCoW frameworks. Roadmapping translates the groomed backlog into a Now/Next/Later horizon document. Agent-generated RICE scores are always marked `[estimate]` — they are hypotheses, not data. Never more than 3 items as P0. Use Now/Next/Later over date-based roadmaps to avoid false precision.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Ungroomed backlogs accumulate low-value items that block visibility of high-impact work. Without systematic prioritization, teams execute on interesting-but-low-value items while critical features wait. LLM agents cannot distinguish strategic P0s from tactical P0s without explicit business context — human validation of prioritization decisions is mandatory before items move to todo/.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Weekly or monthly: agent-assisted grooming session to score and reorder `.aidocs/backlog/`.</item>
        <item>When the backlog exceeds 20 items without re-prioritization in 2+ weeks.</item>
        <item>Starting a new quarter: generate or update roadmap.md from current backlog state.</item>
        <item>When performing MVP scoping: run MoSCoW analysis against a candidate feature set.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>As a replacement for human strategic decisions — P0 prioritization requires business context the agent lacks.</item>
        <item>During active feature execution — grooming is planning work; mixing them degrades both.</item>
        <item>When roadmap.md does not yet exist — create it with human-defined horizons first.</item>
        <item>For items requiring stakeholder input the agent cannot simulate (pricing, partnerships).</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="prioritization-frameworks">
      <p>RICE scoring, MoSCoW classification, and Value vs Effort matrix — when to apply each.</p>

      <section name="rice-scoring">
        <rule>
          <statement>RICE score = (Reach x Impact x Confidence) / Effort. Always flag agent-generated RICE scores with [estimate] — they are hypotheses until validated with real user data.</statement>
          <rationale>Reach and Impact require real user data the agent does not have. Agents systematically assign 100% Confidence; default to 50-80% for agent-generated scores and require justification for 100%.</rationale>
        </rule>

        <example type="good" title="Properly marked RICE scores with estimation flags">
          <code lang="markdown"><![CDATA[| Feature | Reach | Impact | Confidence | Effort | RICE Score | Notes |
|---------|-------|--------|------------|--------|------------|-------|
| Auth refactor | 8 [est] | 2 [est] | 80% [est] | 2 | 6.4 | estimate — needs user research |]]></code>
          <note>Every score tagged [est] so future readers (human and agent) know the data source.</note>
        </example>

        <rule>
          <statement>Use RICE for quarterly roadmap planning and data-driven feature comparison. Require at least Reach and Impact to be estimated before scoring.</statement>
          <rationale>RICE without Reach and Impact estimates is arbitrary ranking with extra steps. Skip RICE if user data is not available and use MoSCoW instead.</rationale>
        </rule>
      </section>

      <section name="moscow-classification">
        <rule>
          <statement>Must items must not exceed 60% of total release scope. If everything is Must, require the team to demote items until the constraint is met.</statement>
          <rationale>Unrestricted Must lists defeat the purpose of MoSCoW. The 60% constraint forces genuine prioritization.</rationale>
        </rule>

        <rule>
          <statement>Document every Won't item with a one-sentence reason and a "when" (Phase 2, v2, never). The Won't-Do section in roadmap.md prevents the same items from being re-proposed in every grooming session.</statement>
          <rationale>Items without explicit exclusion reasoning re-emerge in every planning session, wasting grooming time on decisions already made.</rationale>
        </rule>
      </section>

      <section name="framework-selection">
        <list>
          <item>Quick sprint decisions or resource constraints: MoSCoW.</item>
          <item>Quarterly roadmap with data available: RICE.</item>
          <item>Small team, lightweight process: Value vs Effort 2x2 matrix.</item>
          <item>Strategic theme identification across a large backlog: Outcome-Based (OKR-linked).</item>
        </list>
      </section>
    </section>

    <section name="roadmap-types">
      <p>Now/Next/Later vs time-based vs theme-based roadmaps; why to avoid date-based roadmaps for agents.</p>

      <section name="now-next-later-recommended">
        <rule>
          <statement>Use Now/Next/Later horizon format for roadmap.md. Avoid quarterly dates and specific target months.</statement>
          <rationale>Date-based roadmaps generated by agents introduce false precision — the agent has no knowledge of team velocity, external blockers, or strategic pivots. Now/Next/Later communicates direction without overpromising schedule.</rationale>
        </rule>

        <example type="good" title="Now/Next/Later roadmap with Won't-Do section">
          <code lang="markdown"><![CDATA[## Now (committed, current sprint/month)
- Auth system (P0)
- Landing page

## Next (planned, next quarter)
- Paywall integration
- Content CMS

## Later (exploratory, 6-12 months)
- AI agents
- Mobile app

## Won't Do (This Release)
| Feature | Reason | When |
|---------|--------|------|
| Share Cart URL | Complexity | Phase 3 |
| Price Alerts | External dep | Not planned |]]></code>
        </example>
      </section>

      <section name="theme-based-roadmap">
        <rule>
          <statement>When using theme-based roadmaps, link every theme to a specific metric or constitution goal. Vacuous themes ("User Growth", "Platform Stability") without metric links provide no prioritization signal.</statement>
          <rationale>Agents produce theme labels that sound strategic but are empty without OKR connections. Requiring metric links forces the theme to carry real business weight.</rationale>
        </rule>
      </section>
    </section>

    <section name="agent-limitations">
      <p>Failure modes specific to LLM agents performing backlog grooming and roadmapping tasks.</p>

      <section name="ai-confidence-trap">
        <antipattern>
          <description>Agent-generated backlog items look certain and well-reasoned but are pure hypothesis.</description>
          <reason>LLMs produce polished text that creates false confidence. Text quality does not equal idea quality. Always mark AI-generated items as hypothesis and require user validation before writing a spec.</reason>
        </antipattern>
      </section>

      <section name="score-inflation">
        <antipattern>
          <description>Agent assigns 100% Confidence in RICE scores to almost all items.</description>
          <reason>Agents lack data to justify lower confidence, so they default to 100%. Require explicit justification for Confidence above 80% in agent-generated scores.</reason>
        </antipattern>

        <antipattern>
          <description>Agent assigns high RICE scores to technically interesting items regardless of business value.</description>
          <reason>Agents cannot distinguish strategic P0s from tactical P0s without explicit business context. Human must validate strategic feasibility before items move to todo/.</reason>
        </antipattern>
      </section>

      <section name="pruning-failure">
        <antipattern>
          <description>Agent adds items to backlog but never drops or archives old ones.</description>
          <reason>Agents reword and reorder but rarely delete. Backlogs grow unbounded without explicit cleanup instructions. Archive items older than 6 months with no progress to `.aidocs/backlog/.archive/`.</reason>
        </antipattern>

        <rule>
          <statement>Explicitly instruct the agent to identify items for archival or deletion in every grooming session. Never let the agent add items without also reviewing items for removal.</statement>
          <rationale>Passive accumulation defeats the purpose of grooming. A backlog that only grows degrades the signal-to-noise ratio for future prioritization.</rationale>
        </rule>
      </section>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/backlog-item.md" purpose="Spec stub with RICE fields for a new backlog feature."/>
      <template path="templates/roadmap-skeleton.md" purpose="Now/Next/Later roadmap structure with Won't-Do section."/>
    </templates>

    <see-also>
      <link href="https://www.intercom.com/blog/rice-prioritization-framework/"/>
      <link href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MoSCoW_method"/>
      <link href="https://svpg.medium.com/roadmaps-c04a8f97c18a"/>
    </see-also>
  </content>
</methodology>
